solutions.content:
This is a problem we might be tempted to solve with a brute force approach, directly changing the characters in place at each step, but a quick look at the constraints might make us desist quickly: we might get potentially `50000` `shifts` covering the whole size of `s`, which is of the same size, for a grand total of `250M` operations, which is definitely not the cheapest we can get.

Storing the changes might be much more convenient, but again we need to think how - having an array of `s.size()` elements we update all the time would hardly be an improvement.

Gladly this problem seems to be a handbook case for the usage of a difference array!

The core idea of this data structure is that if we receive a change of `x` across all the values from `a` to `b` (included), we are going to do so just by writing `x` at index `a` and `-x` at index `b + 1` (cancelling the effect of the first change on `a`).

When we go and read through the difference array, we will keep a running count of what changes we encountered, giving us a measure of how they are affecting the current cell. A pretty good solution when we are going to face several changes across potentially very large intervals and when we need to read the final result only once (so we can accept a linear complexity for this!).

Let's go for some quick example, for `"abcdefgh"`:

```cpp
a	b	c	d	e	f	g	h	 // cells of the string	
0	0	0	0	0	0	0	0	 // initial values in the difference array
```

Then we decide to increase by `1` all the values from `1` to `5` , so that we will have:

```cpp
a	b	c	d	e	f	g	h	 // cells of the string	
0	1	0	0	0	0  -1	0	 // values after the first change
```

Now we decide to increase by `1` all the values from `4` to `6` , so that we will have:

```cpp
a	b	c	d	e	f	g	h	 // cells of the string	
0	1	0	0	1	0  -1  -1	 // values after the second change
```

Next we decrease by `1` all the values from `2` to `3` , so that we will have:

```cpp
a	b	c	d	e	f	g	h	 // cells of the string	
0	1  -1	0	2	0  -1  -1	 // values after the third change; notice index 4 now with a value of 2 from the previous two operations
```

Finally we increase by `1` all the values from `3` to `5` , so that we will have:

```cpp
a	b	c	d	e	f	g	h	 // cells of the string	
0	1  -1	1	2	0  -2  -1	 // values after the fourth change; notice index 7 now with a value of -2 from the first and last operations
```

Now, going with a running sun as we parse our difference array, we will find that each character will have to do the following shifts:

```cpp
a	b	c	d	e	f	g	h	 // cells of the string	
0	1   0	1	3	0   1   0	 // shifts for each character
```

The remaining part of the problem is just how to handle when a character gets shifted past `'a'` or `'z'`, but that is rather trivial compared to the rest.

Now, to put our thoughts into code, we will start declaring a few support variables, as usual:
* `len` will store the size of `s`;
* `diffArray` is where we will store our indexes, creating it with a length of `len + 1` to avoid extra logic on the `-x` mark when applied to the last cell - saving us `shifts.size()` conditional statements for the cost of a couple of bytes;
* `dir` will be a support variable for when we iterate `shifts`.

We will then set all the cells of `diffArray` to `0`, but for the last one (as we said, we do not really care and we will never really use it, just as a placeholder).

Looping though each `shift` in `shifts`, we will:
* set `dir` to be `1` if `shift[2]` is also `1`, `-1` otherwise, as specified in the specs;
* increase our starting point `diffArray[shift[0]]` by `dir`;
* decrease our ending point `diffArray[shift[1] + 1]` by `dir`.

With `diffArray` fully populated, we can now work on `s` and, with our ongoing sum `c` initialised to `0` and for each position `i` in it, we will:
* set `c` to increase by `diffArray[i]` (I saw some solutions doing this with a separate pass, but since we only need to do this once, no point in storing the values and writing them down updating `diffArray` in place);
*  set `pos` to the value in which we would pick a character in an ideal `"abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz"` string, with the value equal to the original (`s[i]`), minus `'a'` (to turn it into a value in the `0 - 25` range), plus `c` (so, the final shift for this specific cell);
*  we will add `26` to `pos` as long as it is `< 0` to make sure it is within range;
*  we will subtract `26` to `pos` as long as it is `> 25` to make sure it is within range - notice that this way our solution has only one expensive modulo operation per character 🏆 ;
*  finally, we will set back the value in `s[i]` to be equal to `pos` (our adjusted `0 - 25` final value), plus `'a'` (to make sure it is again a valid lowercase ASCII character).

Once done, we can just `return` `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    string shiftingLetters(string s, vector<vector<int>>& shifts) {
        // support variables
        int len = s.size(), diffArray[len + 1], dir;
        // populating diffArray
        memset(diffArray, 0, len * sizeof(int));
        for (auto &shift: shifts) {
            dir = shift[2] ? 1 : -1;
            diffArray[shift[0]] += dir;
            diffArray[shift[1] + 1] -= dir;
        }
        // populating res
        for (int i = 0, c = 0, pos; i < len; i++) {
            c += diffArray[i];
            pos = s[i] - 'a' + c % 26;
            while (pos < 0) pos += 26;
            while (pos > 25) pos -= 26;
            s[i] = pos += 'a';
        }
        return s;
    }
};
```

