solutions.content:
# First Intuition
We have to update a range so the first idea can be to use an interval tree that updates ranges (in `O(log(n))`) and gets a single value (also in `O(log(n)`)).

# Approach
We construct an interval tree and then update every range from `shifts`.

# Notes
Obviously, when `shifts[i][2]` is `0` we can treat it as `-1` but to avoid if statements (which are typically slower than arithmetic operations) we can multiply it by `2` and then subtract `1`

Secondly, to handle wrapping we can simply do `v mod 26` (we count `a` as `0`, `b` as `1`, and so on). Unfortunately when we for example do `-3%26` we get `-3` instead of `23` to fix this we will do `((v%26) + 26)%26` which gives desired results.

# Complexity
`n` - string length
`m` - shifts count
- Time complexity: `O(nlog(n) + mlog(n))`
  - Constructing tree O(n) - because of creating vector
  - Updating tree with every of m shifts in `O(log(n))` so it's `O(mlog(n))`
  - Reading every of `n` values in `O(log(n))` and making computation in `O(1)` so it's `O(nlog(n))`
- Space complexity: `O(n)`
  - Tree has at worst `2*n - 1` elements, so it's `O(n)`

# Code
```
struct IntervalTree {
    data: Vec<i32>,
    offset: usize,
}

impl IntervalTree {
    pub fn new(n: usize) -> Self {
        let offset = (2usize).pow((n as f64).log2().ceil() as u32); // Calculating how many elements we need to construct binary tree (element at index 0 is never used, root is at 1)
        Self { data: vec![0; offset + n], offset: offset }
    }

    pub fn update(&mut self, mut p: usize, mut q: usize, c: i32) {
        p += self.offset;
        q += self.offset;
        self.data[p] += c;
        if p == q {
            return;
        }
        self.data[q] += c;
        let mut is_p_left = p%2 == 0;
        let mut is_q_right = q%2 == 1;
        p /= 2;
        q /= 2;
        while p != q {
            if is_p_left {
                self.data[p*2 + 1] += c;
            }
            if is_q_right {
                self.data[q*2] += c;
            }
            is_p_left = p%2 == 0;
            is_q_right = q%2 == 1;
            p /= 2;
            q /= 2;
        }
    }

    pub fn get_value(&self, mut i: usize) -> i32 {
        i += self.offset;
        let mut ans = 0;
        while i != 0 {
            ans += self.data[i];
            i /= 2;
        }
        ans
    }
}

impl Solution {
    pub fn shifting_letters(mut s: String, shifts: Vec<Vec<i32>>) -> String {
        let mut tree = IntervalTree::new(s.len());
        for shift in shifts {
            tree.update(shift[0] as usize, shift[1] as usize, shift[2] as i32 * 2 - 1);
        }
        unsafe {    // Code is unsafe because of as_bytes_mut() - but since we are ensured that input is only lowercase english alphabet everything is safe
            for (i, char) in s.as_bytes_mut().into_iter().enumerate() {
                *char = ((((*char as i32 - 97) + tree.get_value(i))%26 + 26)%26) as u8 + 97;
            }
        }
        s
    }
}
```

# Observation
Adding any value to every value of any arbitrary range of whole numbers `[beg; end]` is the same as adding it to every value of `[beg; inf)` and subtracting from every value of `(end; inf)`


# Approach
We create an `array` in which `array[i]` represents a value that should be added to `[i;inf)` and then we fill it with shifts.
Finally, we iterate over the whole string keeping track of the current prefix sum of the `array` and adding it to every element of the string (of course we still have to do some modulo operations).

In other words:
``
s[i] += prefix_sum_of_array[i]
``
``
s[i] = ((s[i]%26) + 26)%26
``

# Complexity
`n` - string length
`m` - shifts count
- Time complexity: `O(n + m)`
  - Creating `array` `O(n)`
  - Filling `array` with every of `m` shifts in `O(1)` each, so it's `O(m)`
  - Iterating over every of `n` element of string and applying changes `O(1)`, so it's `O(n)`

- Space complexity: `O(n)`
  - `array` has `n + 1` elements, so it's `O(n)`

# Code
```
impl Solution {
    pub fn shifting_letters(mut s: String, shifts: Vec<Vec<i32>>) -> String {
        let mut suffix_add = vec![0; s.len() + 1];
        for mut shift in shifts {
            shift[2] += shift[2] - 1;   // turning 0 into -1 (and leaving 1 as 1)
            suffix_add[shift[0] as usize] += shift[2];  // applying change for [beg;inf)
            suffix_add[shift[1] as usize + 1] -= shift[2];  // applying  reversed change for (end; inf)
        }
        unsafe {    // Code is unsafe because of as_bytes_mut() - but since we are ensured that input is only lowercase english alphabet everything is safe
            let s = s.as_bytes_mut();
            let mut it = suffix_add.into_iter();    // We create iterator over suffix_add but it would be perfectly fine to use additional variable to keep track of current position
            let mut n = it.next().unwrap();                     
            for byte in s {                                 // ^... or we can simply enumerate
                *byte = ((((*byte as i32 - 97) + n)%26 + 26)%26) as u8 + 97;    // Whole magic :-) (Notes)
                n += it.next().unwrap();
            }
        }
        s
    }
}
```

