# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Move an interval `[l, r]` forward for 1 alphabet is equivalent to a representation of 
```
[0,...,1,0,0,...,0,-1,0,..,0]
       ^           ^
       l           r+1
prefix sum:
[0,...,1,1,1,...,1,0 ,0,..,0]
```
where the 1 at entry `l` means every element after index `l` are shifted by 1 char forward. The -1 at `r+1` means we are resetting the element after `r+1` backward for one char.

Such representation is accumulative, meaning we can accumulate all the shifts and then compute the total shift of each element. The representation can also be updated in `O(1)` time for each interval shift.

When querying the total shift after all the operations at index `i`, it is equivalent to the prefix sum of `0` to `i` in the above array.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Prefix Sum

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$O(|shift| + n)$

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$O(n)$

