solutions.content:
No panic!  You don't need Union-Find or Segment Tree. 

The drawback for processing `removeQueries` in normal order is you have to maintain all of the segment sums and find out what's the max at the current point from them. The advantage of the reversing approach is you are adding elements back to the `num` and the maximum segment sum will be monotonic therefore you only need to record the current maximum. 

In the meantime, you still need to maintain the valid segments when you add in elements. Two possibilities:
1. the new element is alone by itself
2. the new element is adjacent to the `end` point of the previous segment or/and the `start` point of the segment on its right hand side.

The second above can be maintained with a `jump` table such that `jump[start] = end ` and `jump[end]=start` where `start` and `end` are indices of the starting point and the end point of a segment. And you don't need to take care of the elements in between, since `removeQueries` are all unique so that internal elements will not be exposed once again. 

Lastly, the segment sum can be calculated with a prefix sum array since all the elements within it are all continuous. 


Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(n)

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<long long> maximumSegmentSum(vector<int>& nums, vector<int>& removeQueries) {
        int n = nums.size();
        vector<long long> prefix;
        long long sum = 0; 
        for(int val: nums){
            prefix.push_back(sum);
            sum += val;
        }
        prefix.push_back(sum);

        vector<long long> ans; 
        vector<int> jumps(n,-1);

        long long max_seg_sum = 0;
        ans.push_back(0);
        for(int i=n-1;i>0;i--){
            int start = removeQueries[i], end = removeQueries[i];
            if(start-1>=0 && jumps[start-1]!=-1){
                start = jumps[start-1]; 
            }
            if(end+1<n && jumps[end+1]!=-1){
                end = jumps[end+1];         
            }
            jumps[end] = start;
            jumps[start] = end;

            long long curr_sum = prefix[end+1] - prefix[start];
            if(curr_sum > max_seg_sum){
                max_seg_sum = curr_sum;
            }
            ans.push_back(max_seg_sum);
        }
        reverse(ans.begin(), ans.end());

        return ans;
    }
};
```

