solutions.content:
Use segment tree but instead of storing just sum of the range, store some more information about the range.
Lets say we have a node that will keep information about range [L,R] then we have
1. st , which represents sum starting from index L having all non zero elements.
2. en,  which represents sum ending at index R having all non zero elements.
3. mx,  which represents maximum sum of any subarray between [L,R] having all non zero elements.
4. sum,  which represents sum of all elements in range [L,R].

Now the important thing here is add method that will perform merge operation on two nodes.

```
typedef long long ll;
struct node{
    ll st,en,mx,sum;
};

void add(node& a,node& b,node& c){
    c.st = a.st;
    if(a.st == a.en && a.st == a.sum && a.st != 0)c.st += b.st;

    c.en = b.en;
    if(b.en == b.st && b.sum == b.en && b.en != 0) c.en += a.en;

    c.sum = a.sum + b.sum;
    c.mx = max({a.mx , b.mx, c.st , c.en , a.en + b.st});
}

const int mx = 1e5;
node st[3*mx];

void insert(int ss,int se,int si,const int& idx,const int& val){

    if(ss == se){
