solutions.content:
While going in reverse order of the queries, numbers are inserted at ```index``` and all we have to check is whether adding the number makes it a part of already existing group(segment) or not.
There are 4 cases for this:
1: At  both ```index```-1 and ```index```+1 there is a group.
2: Only at ```index```-1 there is a group.
3: Only at ```index```+1 there is a group.
4: No groups at ```index```-1 and ```index```+1.
For a group three values are needed the ```startingIndex```, ```endingIndex``` and ```sum```.
As we can notice in the above cases we need these values to be present only at the ends of the group and not everywhere in the group as we are not going to make an insertion inside an existing group.
So maintain this information and for every new insertion we can update the values in O(1) time.
For the maximum segment sum as the numbers are positive the max is always increasing so curr_max is max(curr_max , sum of new group which is formed)
at start ```curr_max``` is ```0```
Cases:
1. At  both ```index```-1 and ```index```+1 there is a group.
	These two groups will be merged to one with the current insertion so, values are updated only at the starting index of ```index```-1 group and ending index of ```index```+1 group.
	```newSum``` of new group is 
	```groupinfo[index-1].sum + groupinfo[index+1].sum + nums[index]```

	```newStartingIndex``` is
	```groupinfo[index-1].startingIndex```

