solutions.content:
The energy is simple - we just need the sum of energy of all opponents, plus one.

The experience is trickier, as it depends on the order of opponents.

**C++**
```cpp
int minNumberOfHours(int initialEnergy, int initialExperience, vector<int>& energy, vector<int>& experience) {
    int need_exp = 0, cur_exp = initialExperience;
    for (int i = 0; i < experience.size();  cur_exp += experience[i++])
        need_exp += max(experience[i] - need_exp - cur_exp + 1, 0);
    return max(accumulate(begin(energy), end(energy), 1) - initialEnergy, 0) + need_exp;
}
```

No raw loops version, just for fun. It's neither shorter nor more efficient, just wanted to see if it can be done.

We use prefix sum (partial sum) and transform to compute additional experience we need for each opponent.

**C++**
```cpp
int minNumberOfHours(int initialEnergy, int initialExp, vector<int>& energy, vector<int>& exp) {
    vector<int> ps;
    partial_sum(begin(exp), end(exp), back_inserter(ps));
    transform(begin(ps) + 1, end(ps), begin(ps), begin(exp) + 1, [](int pa, int pb) { return max(pa - 2 * pb, 0); });
    return max(accumulate(begin(energy), end(energy), 1) - initialEnergy, 0) + 
        max(accumulate(begin(exp), end(exp), 0, [](int need, int delta) { return need + max(delta - need + 1, 0); }) - initialExp, 0);
}
```

