We bucket sort (frequency count) the input ```num``` and the rest is straight forward, there are only a few corner cases that need to be handled. See inline comments.

```
    string largestPalindromic(const string& num) {
        // Frequency count.
        array<int, 128> counts = {};
        for (char ch : num) ++counts[ch];

        // Use the largest digits first.
        string front;
        front.reserve(size(num) / 2);
        for (char ch = '9'; ch >= '1'; --ch) {
            if (counts[ch] >= 2) front += string(counts[ch] / 2, ch);
        }

        // If we have used other digits we can use ther zeros too.
        if (!empty(front) && counts['0'] >= 2) front += string(counts['0'] / 2, '0');

        // If we have a odd count us the largest in the center.
        string center;
        for (char ch = '9'; ch >= '0'; --ch) {
            if (counts[ch] & 1) {
                center.push_back(ch);
                break;
            }
        }

        // Special case: only even number of zero digits in the input.
        if (empty(front) && empty(center)) center = "0";

        // Stitch the result together.
        return front + center + string(crbegin(front), crend(front));
    }
```

Time complexity: ```O(n)``` We scan the input once and at most we add ```size(num) / 2``` characters to the string ```front``` and in the end we reverse it once.
Space complexity: ```O(n)``` the string ```front``` grows at most to ```size(num) / 2``` and the rest is just some loop variables.

