solutions.content:
**Algorithm**
1. Count the occurrences of each digit. 
2. Build the `first half part` of the palindrome by appending the digits from 9 to 0 with occurrences more than once. And subtract the occurrences of the digits used to build the palindrome on both sides. To avoid having leading zeros, we do not append `0`  if no digits were added to `first half part` so far. 
3. Find the `middle digit` of the palindrome from the digits from 9 to 0 that still have remaining occurrences. Note if all the digits are 0, `first half part` is empty and `middle digit` is `0`.
4. Build the palindrome by concatenating: `first half part + middle digit + reversed first half part`



**Java Code**

```java
class Solution {
    public String largestPalindromic(String num) {
        // find the occurrences of each digit
        int[] count = new int[10];
        for (char digit: num.toCharArray()) {
            ++count[digit - '0'];
        }

        // build the mirrored part of the palindrome
        StringBuilder mirror = new StringBuilder();
        for (int digit = 9; digit >= 0; --digit) {
            if (count[digit] > 1) {
                // avoid leading zeros
                if (digit == 0 && mirror.length() == 0) {
                    continue;
                }
                // append half of the occurrences to mirror
                for (int i = 0; i < count[digit] / 2; ++i) {
                    mirror.append(digit);
                }
                // subtract the occurrences used on both sides
                count[digit] %= 2;
            }
        }

        // find the middle digit
        String mid = "";
        for (int digit = 9; digit >= 0; --digit) {
            if (count[digit] > 0) {
                mid += digit;
                break;
            }
        }

		// build the palindrome and return it
        StringBuilder ret = new StringBuilder();
        ret.append(mirror);
        ret.append(mid);
        ret.append(mirror.reverse());
        return ret.toString();
    }
}
```

