**Intution** : Let's begin by thinking that the largest number can only be achieved when we place the largest digit at the most significant place in the number. 

**Method** : Begin by storing the count of each digit. Traverse again from 0 to 9 and form the string with all the **digits which have even counts** in the following way : 

```
Take the smallest number in the middle of the string so that it looks like.
..33221100112233...
```

For the digits with odd counts (n) : take n-1 occurences into the string and find the maximum digit with an odd count , because **that needs to be placed in the middle of the final palindromic string.**

That's it. !

Here is the C++ implementation.

```
class Solution {
public:
    string largestPalindromic(string num) {
        int n = num.length();
        vector<int> mp(10 , 0);
        for( int i = 0 ;i < n ; i++){
            mp[num[i] - '0']++;
        }
        string ans = "";
        int maxOne = INT_MIN;
        for(int i = 0 ;i < 10 ;i++){
            int times = mp[i]/2;
            ans = std::string(times,i+'0') + ans + std::string(times , i + '0');
            if(mp[i]%2){
                maxOne = max( maxOne , i);
            }
        }
        if(maxOne != INT_MIN)
            ans.insert( ans.length()/2 , to_string(maxOne));
        int i = 0;
        while(i < ans.size()){
            if( ans[i] != '0'){
                break;
            }
            i++;
        }
        ans =  ans.substr(i , ans.length() - i*2);
        if( ans == ""){
            return "0";
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

