# Intuition
Larger numbers will always have either more digits, or larger digits to the left.

"99" > "89"
"123" < "321"
"12" > "3"

Thus to create a largest palindrome, you want the left side of the string to be all digits with a frequency count of at least 2 in descending order.

# Approach
1. Create a frequency map sorted in descending order by key.
2. Iterate over the map, add all pairs of digits you can in the middle of your result. The progression looks like: `""` -> `"77"` -> `"7447"` -> `"744447"`. Note that beginning with any `0s` results in an invalid number.
3. If there are any remaining entries in the map with a value of `1`, add the highest value one in the middle of the string.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: `O(N)`
We insert N elements in a TreeMap, but the TreeMap will only ever contain 9 entries, thus `O(N log 9)` -> `O(N)`
Iterating over `num` requires checking all elements in `num`: `O(N)`
Note that iterating over the map is only `O(9)`

- Space complexity: `O(1)`
Maximum of 9 possible entries in the map.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    fun largestPalindromic(num: String): String {
        val tm = TreeMap<Int, Int>(compareByDescending<Int> { it })
        // Creates a digit frequency count, then adds to TreeMap
        num.groupingBy { it - '0' }.eachCount().let {
            tm.putAll(it)
        }
        val sb = StringBuilder()
        for ((key, value) in tm) {
            if (key == 0 && sb.length == 0) continue
            while (tm.getValue(key) > 1) {
                val mid = sb.length / 2
                sb.insert(mid, key)
                sb.insert(mid, key)
                tm[key] = tm.getValue(key) - 2
            }
        }
        for ((key, value) in tm) {
            if (value > 0) {
                val mid = sb.length / 2
                sb.insert(mid, key)
                break
            }
        }
        return sb.toString()
    }
}
```

