# Intuition
Use a frequency map implemented by array where the index is the integer and the value is the frequency.
# Approach
This solution uses the counter approach, where we count the frequency of each individual integer, then we find how many pairs we have it appears two or more times, and we calculate the middle element as the first highest element to have a frequency of 1, then we concatenate the answers at the end all while optimizing for edge cases, like leading zeros and large numbers.
# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N) because for each i between 0 and 9, freq[i]*10 is equal to N.
- Space complexity: O(1) Since we only used an array of 10 characters long.

# Code
```
function largestPalindromic(num: string): string {
  let freq = new Array(10).fill(0), ans = '', mid:String = undefined

  // Create freq map

  for ( let i = 0; i < num.length; i++ ) {
    freq[Number(num[i])]++
  }

  // Iterate over freq map and decrement all values > or = than 2 by 2, while pushing i into the output

  for ( let i = 10; i >= 0; i-- ) { // iterate from 10 to 0
    while ( freq[i] > 1 ) {         // while pairs are available
      ans += i                      // push i into output
      freq[i] -= 2                  // decrement counter by 2
    }
    if ( mid === undefined && freq[i] === 1 ) {
      mid = i.toString()            // this finds the largest possible middle integer
    }
  }

  ans = BigInt(ans).toString()      // this removes leading zeros

  if ( Number(ans) === 0 ) {        // this fixes the '00' case
    if ( mid === undefined ) return '0'
    else ans = ''                   // this fixes the '00900' case
  } 

  // finally return ans concatenated with itself reversed, while adding the middle integer if it exists

  return ans + (mid ? mid : '') + ans.split('').reverse().join('')
};
```

