                for(int i = 0; i < adj[u].size(); i++)
                {
                     // if adjacent nodes are not visited, push them into the queue
                    if(!visited[adj[u][i]]) 
                        q.push(adj[u][i]);
                }
            }
            ans++;       // keep a count for the traversal
        }   
    }
    int amountOfTime(TreeNode* root, int start) {
        // vector to store the graph
        vector<vector<int>> adj(100001);
        // vector to check which nodes are visited
        vector<bool> visited(100001, false);

        buildGraph(root, adj);
        bfs(adj, visited, start);
        // return ans - 1, coz the start node is also counted in traversal, but it was already infeced
        return ans - 1;
    }
};
```

solutions.content:
**1 pass / dfs / recursive with helper**
**time: `O(n)`; space: `O(N)`(call stack)**

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/c3141aa5-169b-456b-be05-ad5e2370b7c8_1662368831.081831.png)

So basically all points are either "below" `s` (gray nodes) or "above/equal" it (red nodes and green node) in the tree. 

The parent node needs to know weither it's two children are gray nodes or not. Depending on the answer it uses different expressions to update the `out` variable that stores the answer to the problem and a `return` value.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/f1fd258c-3966-41bf-8f0e-3c409c49bbd9_1662374245.5740168.png)

```
class Solution 
{
    int out{};
    pair<int, int> f(TreeNode* n, int s)
    {
        if(!n) return {-1,0};
        auto l = f(n->left,  s),
             r = f(n->right, s);
        if(n->val==s)
        {
            out = max(out, 1+max(l.first, r.first));
            return {0,1};
        }
        if(l.second or r.second)
        {
            out = max(out, 2+l.first+r.first);
            return {1+l.first*l.second+r.first*r.second, 1};
        }
        return {1+max(l.first, r.first), 0};
    }
public:    
    int amountOfTime(TreeNode* n, int s)
    {
        f(n, s);
        return out; 
    }
};
```
**Notation:**
`f` function returns a pair of numbers. The second one indicates weither this node is
* red/green(`1`) or
* gray(`0`).
* 
Using `int's` instead of `booleans` allows to use them in arithmetic expressions like this 
```
return {1+l.first*l.second+r.first*r.second, 1};
```
that makes the code a bit shorter. The reason for passing `0` or `1`. for the calee is that depending on that we have to use two different formulas: one involves `max` function
```
 return {1+max(l.first, r.first), 0};
```
the other one involves `+`operator
```
return {1+l.first*l.second+r.first*r.second, 1};
```
Also they update `out` variable in different ways.

As for the first number that `f` returns it's either 
* the longest path from the current node to the leaf **for gray nodes** or 
* the longest path from the current node to the green node **for red nodes**.

Another problem: [742. Closest Leaf in a Binary Tree](https://leetcode.com/problems/closest-leaf-in-a-binary-tree/discuss/2535358/dfs)

