solutions.content:
This is my contest solution. It's very similar to the leetcode question where it asks you to find *The Diameter of a Tree*. 
We have a global variable that tracks the maximum value.
Then we do DFS, there are basically 3 cases to handle.
1. When the current node is our target, we update the answer to the max of depth from both its chlidren.
2. When the current Tree rooted at it does **not** contain the target node, we should return the maximum depth to its parent.
3. When the current Tree rooted at it contains the target node, we update answer = `max(dist from current node to target + maxDepth from the other child)`


`Time O(N)`
`Space O(Height of Tree)`
```Java
class Solution {
    int res = 0;
    public int amountOfTime(TreeNode root, int start) {
        dfs(root, start);
        return res;
    }

    int[] dfs(TreeNode root, int start){
        int[] ans = new int[2]; // [value, whether this tree contains target]
        if (root == null){
            return ans;
        }
        int[] L = dfs(root.left, start);
        int[] R = dfs(root.right, start);
        if (root.val == start){ // case 1
            ans[1] = ans[0] = 1; // reset depth and set ans[1] = 1, meaning this subtree now contains target
            res = Math.max(L[0], R[0]);
            return ans;
        }
        if (R[1]+L[1] >= 1){ // case 3
            ans[1] = 1;
            res = Math.max(res, L[0] + R[0]);
            ans[0] = R[1] == 1? R[0] : L[0]; // return the depth from current node to target and discard the other one.
        }else{ // case 2
            ans[0] = Math.max(R[0], L[0]);
        }
        ans[0]++; // increment depth
        return ans;
    }
}
```

